There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of psychological interventions to reduce anxiety in children undergoing surgery.

There is currently insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of exercise as an adjunctive treatment for women with breast cancer. There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of acupuncture in the treatment of acute ischaemic stroke. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered randomised controlled trials with adequate methodological rigour and adequate reporting of outcomes.

Therejuvant chemotherapy is effective in delaying the start of chemotherapy in women with node-positive breast cancer. However, there is no evidence to support the use of adjuvant chemotherapy in patients with lymph nodes.

There found no evidence to support or refute the use of vitamin E supplements in the prevention of CVD. There is some evidence to support the use of music as a non-invasive treatment for children with cancer and other painful medical procedures. There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of serum markers of aseptic loosening after total hip arthroplasty for osteoarthritis.

There found no evidence to support or refute the use of maternal influenza vaccination during pregnancy to reduce the risk of maternal death, neonatal mortality and infant morbidity in pregnant women.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of any specific dietary intervention for children or adults with ALL who have suffered from ALL.

Therealimumab is an effective induction therapy for the maintenance of clinical remission in patients with CD with infliximab disease, and is associated with a reduction in the incidence of adverse events and the use of steroid withdrawal. There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of recombinant vaccines to prevent seroconversion in immunocompromised patients with CKD.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of action observation for improving walking ability after stroke. There is a need for well-conducted randomised controlled trials with low risk of bias and high methodological quality.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of palliative surgery in patients with advanced gastric cancer.

There-adjuvanted vaccines are effective in reducing the prevalence of influenza p and emic disease in children aged six months to 18 years of age. However, there is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered and reported randomised controlled trials to assess the efficacy of vaccine adjuvant versus inactivated split-virus vaccines.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of adjuvant chemotherapy in patients with stage I or II NSCLC.

There is some evidence to support the use of technology-based interventions for dementia carers. However, there is a need for well-designed, adequately powered and reported randomised controlled trials to evaluate the effects of such interventions on quality of life, satisfaction with care, health-related stress and depression among caregivers.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to determine the effect of vaccination on the immune response to influenza vaccination in people aged 65 years or older.

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of self-management programmes for patients with chronic disease. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up.
There is insufficient evidence to determine whether adjuvant influenza vaccines are more effective than single-dose vaccines in preventing influenza infection in children and young people.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of oral corticosteroids in the treatment of TMJ osteoarthritis.

There patients with moderate to severe plaque psoriasis, ustekinumab and infliximab are effective in improving the quality of life of patients and improving psoriatic arthritis-related outcomes. Theremega-3 fatty acids appear to be safe and well tolerated in the treatment of depression and anxiety disorders in adults and children. There is no evidence to support or refute the use of omega-3 as an adjunctive treatment for depression or anxiety disorders.
There is not enough evidence to evaluate the effects of weight loss interventions on asthma control or quality of life in adults or children with asthma.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support the use of music therapy in cancer patients undergoing cancer treatment.

There is some evidence to support the use of pharmacists as part of a healthcare team to reduce the number of medications prescribed to people aged 65 years or older in care homes. There is currently insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of backward walking training for people with cerebral palsy. There found no evidence to support or refute the use of calcium supplementation during pregnancy to reduce the incidence of pre-eclampsia and preterm birth in women with low dietary calcium intake.

There is some evidence to support the use of postcards to increase immunization rates among children aged two to 59 years of age. However, this evidence is limited by the small number of studies included in this review, the small sample sizes, and the lack of reporting of studies. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered, and adequately reported RCTs that measure the effect of postcard reminders on immunisation rates.

There found no evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of zinc supplementation during pregnancy to reduce the incidence of childhood and neonatal morbidity and mortality in children under five years of age.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of mechanical ventilation in children with acute respiratory distress syndrome. There is a need for well-designed, well-conducted and reported randomized controlled trials comparing mechanical ventilation versus conventional ventilation.

There combination hepatitis A and B vaccines are effective in protecting against hepatitis B and hepatitis B viruses, but the effect on seroprotection and immunogenicity needs to be evaluated in larger trials.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of preterm formula to prevent or delay weight gain in preterm infants. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials comparing preterm and low-birthweight infants with different protein and energy intakes.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of conjugate vaccines to prevent invasive H. influenzae type b disease.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of ankle-foot orthoses in people with or without hemiparesis due to stroke or traumatic brain injury.

There is some evidence that acupuncture may have a beneficial effect on allergic rhinitis. However, there is a need for further well-designed RCTs to investigate the effectiveness of acupuncture in this condition. Such trials should be of high methodological quality and should be adequately powered to detect clinically important differences.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of psychological interventions to prevent or delay the onset of depression or anxiety disorders in people aged 65 years or older.

There is some evidence to support the use of computer-based interventions for the management of depression and anxiety. There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of educational interventions for children with asthma. There is a need for well designed, conducted and reported randomised controlled trials comparing educational interventions with other forms of asthma management.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the effectiveness of mental practice after stroke for improving upper limb function after stroke.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of dietary interventions during pregnancy to reduce the risk of preterm birth or gestational diabetes.
There found no evidence to support or refute the use of music during colonoscopy for reducing anxiety or pain in patients undergoing invasive procedures.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of quadrivalent inactivated influenza vaccines ( TIVs) to protect against influenza A, B, and C lineages from influenza A and C. However, there is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered, double-blinded, placebo-controlled trials comparing the efficacy of TIV versus TIV in adults and children.

There addition of triple therapy to inhaled corticosteroids in patients with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) improves lung function and lung function in patients who are at high risk of exacerbations and who do not have a history of asthma.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of case management interventions in older people with dementia. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up to assess the effects of case-management interventions on quality of life, functional ability, and cost-effectiveness.

There fortified foods appear to be effective in reducing the prevalence of vitamin A deficiency in children aged six months to 12 years of age. However, there is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of fortified foods in this population. There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support the use of balance training interventions in people with hemiplegic stroke. There is a need for well-conducted, well-designed and reported RCTs in this area.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of interventions to improve adherence to dialysis services in people with end-stage renal disease. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials with low risk of bias and high methodological quality.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of dietary and lifestyle interventions during pregnancy to prevent pregnancy weight gain.
There found no evidence to support or refute the use of oral corticosteroids for the maintenance of remission in patients with Crohn's disease.
There is no evidence to support or refute the use of adjuvant chemotherapy in patients with muscle-invasive bladder cancer.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of constraint-induced movement therapy in people with acute or subacute stroke.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of educational interventions to reduce television viewing in children and adolescents. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered and reported randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up to determine whether educational interventions are effective in reducing television viewing.
There is no evidence to support or refute the use of sorafenib in the treatment of patients with RCC.

There review suggests that adjuvant chemotherapy for women with early stage cervical cancer is superior to chemotherapy alone in terms of overall survival, disease free survival and disease-free survival in patients with early stages cervical cancer. There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of pre-stroke rehabilitation for people with moderate to severe acute stroke.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of any intervention for the rehabilitation of the upper extremity after stroke.

There is no evidence to support or refute the use of perioperative chemotherapy in patients with advanced stage IIIA non-small cell lung cancer. There is a need for well-conducted RCTs to evaluate the effects of this treatment option.

There is some evidence to support the use of expressive writing interventions in patients with cancer. However, there is a need for further well-designed RCTs to evaluate the effects of expressive written interventions on quality of life and health outcomes in cancer patients.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of acupuncture for post-stroke depression. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered randomised controlled trials comparing acupuncture with other pharmacological treatments for post stroke depression.

Thereiotropium is an effective bronchodilator in the treatment of moderate to severe COPD. Its use is associated with a reduction in the rate of exacerbations and hospital admissions, but it is not clear whether this effect is clinically important.

There is some evidence that prehabilitation may improve the quality of life of patients undergoing surgery for cancer. However, there is a paucity of high-quality, well-designed and reported randomised controlled trials evaluating the effects of postoperative rehabilitation on short-term and long-term outcomes.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of antibiotics to reduce exacerbations of COPD. Further research is required to establish the role of antibiotics in reducing exacerbations and improving lung function.

There is some evidence to support the use of psychosocial interventions to reduce psychological distress in cancer patients. There is not enough evidence to support the use of omega-3 fatty acids as an add-on treatment for people with depression or bipolar disorder.

There found no evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of zinc supplementation during pregnancy for preventing or treating childhood or neonatal morbidity and mortality in children.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of platelet-rich plasma for sinus floor augmentation in adults with sinus disease.

There-daily inhaled bronchodilators with long-acting β2-agonists appear to be more effective than short-acting inhaled corticosteroids in improving lung function and reducing the risk of exacerbations in patients with COPD. There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of any specific dietary or physical activity intervention for postpartum weight loss. Theemetrexed maintenance therapy in patients with advanced non-squamous NSCLC is associated with a statistically significant improvement in OS, PFS and disease progression-free survival compared with first-line therapy. There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support the routine use of dietary supplements in patients with COPD.

Thereacheostomy is associated with a reduction in the number of days of mechanical ventilation and the length of stay in the ICU. There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support the use of brief interventions to reduce alcohol consumption or alcohol-related problems in healthcare settings.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of laser therapy in the treatment of chronic pain in adults or children.

Thereercise is an effective and safe intervention for the management of fatigue in women with cancer. Exercise may also be associated with a reduction in the incidence of adverse events, such as nausea and vomiting. There is no evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of low glycaemic index diets for women with gestational diabetes mellitus. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered trials to assess the effects of this diet on pregnancy outcomes.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of electroacupuncture for the treatment of depression or chronic pain. There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of neuromuscular stimulation after stroke for improving upper extremity motor function after stroke. There is a need for well-conducted randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up.

There-acting β2-agonists are effective in improving FEV1 in patients with moderate to severe COPD. However, they do not appear to have a statistically significant effect on mortality or cardiovascular morbidity. Further well-designed RCTs are needed to confirm these findings.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of health promotion interventions for women and their partners. There is a need for well designed, conducted, reported and reported randomised controlled trials with adequate methodological rigour and adequate reporting of outcome measures.

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of peer support interventions for people with type 2 diabetes. There is a need for well-conducted RCTs with low risk of bias and well reported outcome measures.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to determine whether immunization of health-care workers against influenza infection reduces mortality or morbidity among patients with acute or chronic leukaemia.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of interventions to improve immunisation uptake in developing countries. There is a need for well-designed and reported RCTs to assess the effects of interventions on immunization uptake.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of lipid-based nutrient supplements in children. There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of virtual reality in the treatment of people with stroke. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered randomised controlled trials with adequate methodological rigour and adequate reporting of results.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of ad libitum feeding regimens for preterm infants with chronic hypoglycaemic episodes.

There is an urgent need for well-designed, adequately-powered and reported trials that evaluate the effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of interventions targeting return to work.

There found no evidence to support or refute the use of CSR in patients with ESCLC. However, CSR is associated with a significant reduction in the risk of brain metastases and neuropsychological syndromes when compared with no CSR. Further research is needed to determine the optimal CSR dose, duration and intensity for CSR and CSR, as well as to assess CSR as an adjuvant to CSR treatment in patients who are in complete remission or who do not have brain metastasis.

There found no evidence to support the use of psychosocial interventions to reduce the incidence of insomnia in women with cancer. However, there is a need for well-designed and reported randomised controlled trials with adequate power to detect the effects of these interventions on women's quality of life.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of any particular ventilatory strategy in patients with acute lung injury or ARDS who are ventilated with low PEEP levels.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of psychosocial interventions in patients with inflammatory bowel disease.

There-valent Pneumococcal conjugate vaccine is effective in reducing the incidence of invasive pneumococcal disease in children aged less than two years of age, and preventing the first episode of radiologically confirmed AOM in children younger than 12 months of age. There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of topical analgesics to reduce pain during immunization procedures in term newborns.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of psychosocial interventions for people with dementia and their carers. There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of Sahaja Yoga meditation for treating depression, anxiety or anxiety disorders.

There is some evidence that caregiver education and training interventions are effective in improving caregiver knowledge, knowledge and skills in caring for a relative with dementia. There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of CPAP in the treatment of OSA. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials comparing CPAP with other pharmacological treatments for OSA, such as oral appliances and sleep apnoea.

Thefliximab is an effective and safe rescue therapy for patients with moderately to severely active ulcerative colitis. It is not clear whether infliximab has a role in the maintenance of remission in patients with moderate to severe disease.

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of tDCS for treating neuropathic pain in people with SCI. There found no evidence to support or refute the use of chemoradiation in the treatment of anal cancer.

There is insufficient evidence to determine whether glucocorticoids are beneficial or harmful for patients undergoing surgery for esophageal cancer. There is currently insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of aerobic exercise in children with asthma. There is no evidence to support or refute the use of NPPV in the management of critically ill patients. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials to evaluate the effectiveness of this intervention.

There is insufficient evidence to support the routine use of massage therapy in palliative care. There is a need for well-conducted RCTs that compare massage therapy with other forms of health-related quality of life improvement in patients and carers.
There found no evidence to support or refute the use of adjuvant radiotherapy in patients with locally advanced head and neck squamous cell carcinoma.

There is a need for well designed randomised controlled trials with long term follow up, that compare acupuncture with other treatments for chronic pain, and that trials comparing acupuncture to other treatments are justified.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of DCI in the treatment of women with polycystic ovary syndrome.

There found no evidence to support or refute the use of Web-based interventions to help smokers quit. There is a need for well-designed and reported randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up to determine the effectiveness of such interventions.

There is some evidence that caregiver skill-building interventions can improve the quality of life of people with dementia and their carers. However, this evidence is based on only a small number of studies and is not sufficient to draw firm conclusions about the effectiveness of such interventions. Further research is needed to identify the most effective and most cost effective components of caregiver skills building interventions, as well as to identify which components are most effective, most cost-effective and most effective.

Thereercise during pregnancy is associated with a reduction in maternal and perinatal morbidity and mortality when compared with no exercise during pregnancy. Exercise during pregnancy appears to be associated with an increase in the risk of postpartum weight gain.

There is some evidence that framing of HPV vaccines to prevent genital warts increases uptake of the vaccine. However, there is not enough evidence to assess the effect of framing on uptake of vaccination. There is a need for well-conducted and reported RCTs to investigate the effects of framing of vaccination to different age groups and settings.

Thereercise for women diagnosed with or at risk of breast cancer has been shown to be safe and effective in reducing the risk of all-cause mortality, lymphedema, osteoporosis, and other adverse events. Exercise is associated with a decreased risk of fractures, but there is insufficient evidence to determine whether exercise is safe or effective for women with or without breast cancer.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of psychosocial interventions for the management of fatigue in cancer patients.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to determine whether magnesium supplementation during pregnancy is beneficial or harmful for preventing pregnancy-induced leg cramps.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of chemoradiation in patients with locally advanced pancreatic cancer undergoing resectation.

Thereercise during pregnancy may reduce the risk of maternal and neonatal morbidity and mortality when compared with no intervention or control group. However, there is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of exercise during pregnancy to reduce maternal morbidity or mortality.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of systemic chemotherapy in patients with peritoneal PC. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered, double-blinded, placebo-controlled trials comparing systemic chemotherapy with or without cytoreductive surgery for patients with PC.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of dietary fat in relation to prostate cancer incidence or mortality. There is a need for well designed randomised controlled trials with adequate power to detect and report adverse events.

The is currently no evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of MSCs in the treatment of osteoarthritis of the knee. There is a need for well-designed RCTs to evaluate the efficacy and safety of stem cell therapy in this population.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of micronutrient supplements to prevent or delay the onset of severe malnutrition in children.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of psychosocial interventions for people with chronic disease. There is a need for well designed, conducted and reported randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up.

There is not enough evidence to support the use of psychosocial interventions for caregivers of cancer patients. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials that address the needs of caregivers and their carers.
There is no evidence to support or refute the use of adjuvant chemotherapy for women with node-positive breast cancer.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of neuromobilisation as a treatment for sensory impairments after stroke.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support the use of non-invasive ventilation as a first line intervention in patients with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to determine whether iron supplementation during pregnancy is beneficial or harmful for women or children.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of psychosocial interventions for the treatment of prostate cancer. There is a need for well designed, conducted, reported and reported randomised controlled trials with adequate methodological rigour and adequate sample sizes.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of electromyographic biofeedback for the rehabilitation of the upper limb after stroke. There is a need for well-conducted, well-designed and reported RCTs with adequate methodological rigour and adequate reporting of outcome measures.

Thereral inhaled corticosteroids and formoterol are effective in reducing the number of exacerbations of COPD and improving lung function in patients with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) who have asthma or who have a history of asthma. In patients with COPD who do not have asthma, inhaler therapy, or who do have an asthma exacerbation, the combination of inhaled and oral steroids may be more effective than inhaled steroids alone or in patients who do.
There found no evidence to support or refute the use of daily or twice weekly iron supplementation for children with iron deficiency anemia in developing countries.

There is some evidence that self-management interventions are effective in improving self-efficacy and energy levels among people with chronic disease. However, there is a need for well-designed, well-conducted and reported randomised controlled trials with low risk of bias and high methodological quality to identify the most effective interventions for improving health-related quality of life.

The isoproterenol and formoterol appear to have similar bronchodilator efficacy to inhaled corticosteroids in adults with mild to moderate asthma. However, there is no evidence that inhaled beta2-agonists are more effective than salbutamol or salmeterol. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered, double-blinded, placebo-controlled trials to determine the relative effectiveness and safety of these drugs.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of dietary interventions targeting dietary patterns associated with a reduction in the risk of dementia or frailty in older people.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of acupuncture for the treatment of sepsis or early septic shock. Further trials are needed to determine whether acupuncture has a role in the treatment or prevention of Sepsis infection.

There found no evidence to support or refute the use of zinc supplementation during pregnancy for preventing or treating neonatal morbidity and mortality in pregnant women or their newborns. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered randomised controlled trials to assess the effects of supplementation on neonatal mortality and morbidity.

There patients with moderate to severe plaque psoriasis, infliximab and etanercept are effective in reducing the risk of disease progression in patients with psoriatic arthritis. However, there is a lack of evidence on the long-term efficacy and safety of these agents, and further research is needed.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of videogames for improving balance in older adults.

There is insufficient evidence to draw conclusions about the effectiveness of psychosocial interventions for the caregiving of people with dementia and their carers. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered randomised controlled trials that assess the effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of interventions.

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of vestibular rehabilitation for people with VSP. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up to assess the effects of exercise on VSP and its complications.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of robotic pet therapy for people with dementia. There is a need for well-conducted randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up and to investigate the effects of robot therapy on quality of life in older people and their caregivers.

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of oral appliances for the treatment of OSA. There is a need for well-designed and reported randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up.

There-Friendly Hospital Initiative ( BFHI) programmes are effective in increasing breastfeeding duration and exclusivity among women who are exclusively breastfed. There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of BFHI programmes in promoting breastfeeding in healthcare settings.
There is not enough evidence to support routine use of the pneumococcal vaccine in the prevention of pneumonia in people aged 65 years or older.

There is some evidence to support the use of telephone-based support groups for caregivers of people with dementia. However, there is not enough evidence to evaluate the effectiveness of such interventions.
[Note: The four citations in the awaiting classification section of the Review may alter the conclusions of the review once assessed.]

The is currently no evidence to support or refute the use of any dietary intervention for the treatment of NAFLD. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up to assess the effects of dietary interventions on NAFLDs.

There found no evidence to support or refute the use of Internet-based interventions for the management of depression and other chronic illnesses. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered trials that evaluate the effects of IHCAs on health-related quality of life outcomes and disease-related morbidity and mortality.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of platinum based regimens for the treatment of patients with CUP. Combination chemotherapy with gemcitabine, cisplatin and carboplatin appears to be an effective treatment option for patients with unknown primary site carcinoma.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of inhaled beta2-agonists in the management of asthma exacerbations.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of multinutrient supplementation in the management of physical frailty in older adults.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of psychosocial interventions in dementia care. There is a need for well-designed and reported randomised controlled trials to investigate the effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of interventions in this population.

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of dietary interventions to reduce liver fat in people with NAFLD. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered randomised controlled trials with adequate power to detect clinically important changes in liver fat.
There is no evidence to support or refute the use of oral corticosteroids in the treatment of acute asthma exacerbations in children.

Thereiclesonide is an inhaled corticosteroid prodrug that is effective in reducing the use of inhaled steroids in patients with persistent asthma. However, there is insufficient evidence to support its use as a first line treatment in people with asthma.

There current evidence does not support the use of transcranial direct current stimulation in the treatment of people with aphasia. However, there is a need for well designed, adequately powered and reported randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up.
There found no evidence to support or refute the use of closed versus open endotracheal suctioning systems for ventilator-associated pneumonia in patients with mechanical ventilation.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of antioxidant supplements in patients with chronic hepatitis C virus infection. There is a need for well-designed RCTs with adequate allocation concealment and reporting of adverse events.
The is evidence that platinum-containing chemotherapy regimens improve overall survival and OS in patients with advanced non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC) when compared with chemotherapy alone.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of inhaled nitric oxide as a biomarker of airway inflammation in patients with COPD.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of platelet-rich plasma injections for the treatment of knee osteoarthritis. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered, well-conducted and reported randomised controlled trials comparing platelet rich plasma injections with other methods of cartilage regeneration.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of preoperative radiotherapy in patients with squamous cell carcinoma of the oral cavity or oropharyngeal cavity.

Thereatment of women with HER2-positive breast cancer with trastuzumab plus adjuvant chemotherapy is associated with a significant improvement in disease-free survival, distant DFS event rate and overall survival. However, there is no evidence to support or refute this.

There is not enough evidence to evaluate the effects of physical activity referral schemes on health-related physical activity behaviour change. There is a need for well-designed RCTs that evaluate the effectiveness of interventions based on behavioural, cognitive or behavioural change theories, as well as well-conducted randomised controlled trials with adequate sample sizes.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the routine use of human milk fortified with human faecal secretions to prevent NEC in extremely preterm infants.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of exhaled nitric oxide as a diagnostic test for asthma or allergic rhinitis.

There is currently insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of preoperative warm-up exercises for laparoscopic surgery. There is a need for well-conducted randomised controlled trials with low risk of bias in the design and reporting of such trials.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of peritoneal chemotherapeutic agents in patients with gastric cancer.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of hyaluronan gel as an adjunctive treatment for chronic periodontitis.

There is no evidence to support the use of inhaled beta2-agonists in patients with chronic asthma. There is a need for well-designed and reported randomised controlled trials with adequate sample size and duration of follow up.

There review suggests that there is little evidence to support the use of question-asking techniques in the management of patients with breast cancer. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials with low risk of bias and high quality reporting of results.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of constraint-induced movement therapy in children with cerebral palsy. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered randomised controlled trials comparing the effects of CIMT and bimanual training.

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of context ual interference in the acquisition and transfer of motor skills. There is a need for well-conducted randomised controlled trials that examine the effects of contextual interventions on acquisition and retention of motor skill competencies.
There is no evidence to support or refute the use of adjuvant chemotherapy in patients with metastatic gastric cancer.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of cognitively stimulating interventions in the management of dementia in older people.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of inhaled corticosteroids in children with asthma. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered, double-blinded, placebo-controlled trials to determine the long-term efficacy and safety of inhalation therapy.

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of theories of planned behaviour for preventing or treating diabetes. Future trials should investigate the extent and type of theory used to guide behaviour change, the types of theories used, and the type of intervention used.
[Note: The four citations in the awaiting classification section of the review may alter the conclusions of the reviewed review once assessed.]

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of aerobic exercise for men with prostate cancer. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered randomised controlled trials comparing aerobic exercise with usual care in men with cancer.

There is some evidence that electroacupuncture is effective in reducing the incidence of PONV in patients undergoing open heart surgery. However, there is not enough evidence to support or refute its use in clinical practice. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials with adequate power to detect and report clinically important outcomes such as mortality, morbidity and neurodevelopmental outcomes.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of glyburide for women with gestational diabetes mellitus or GDM.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of rTMS in the treatment of people with subacute Aphasia following stroke.

There is some evidence to support the use of brief interventions to increase the uptake of screening and brief interventions for people with alcohol-related risk factors in primary care settings. However, there is not enough evidence to evaluate the effectiveness of interventions to change attitudes towards alcohol use disorders in healthcare settings. There is a need for well designed, conducted and reported randomised controlled trials to assess the effect of interventions on change in attitudes, behaviour, and health outcomes in health settings.

Theapatinib combination of trastuzumab and lapatinib significantly increases the rate of pathological complete response ( pCR) in women with HER2-positive primary breast cancer. Lapatinib is an adjuvant therapy for HER2 positive metastatic breast cancer, but it is also associated with a higher incidence of adverse events.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of psychosocial interventions for stroke survivors and their carers. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the effectiveness of driving simulator training for people with motor impairments after stroke.

There is some evidence to support the effectiveness of cooking classes in promoting healthy eating habits among children. However, there is a paucity of high quality RCTs on this topic and more research is needed to confirm or refute these findings.
There evidence from RCTs to support the use of neoadjuvant chemotherapy in women with locally advanced squamous cell carcinoma of the cervix is weak and inconclusive.

There is insufficient evidence to assess the effects of food insecurity on pregnancy outcomes. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered randomised controlled trials that assess the impact of food insecure in pregnancy on maternal and infant health outcomes.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of antenatal vitamin D supplementation during pregnancy to reduce the risk of preterm birth and neonatal death. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered randomised controlled trials with adequate power to detect clinically important differences in mortality and morbidity.
There found no evidence to support or refute the use of iron supplements during pregnancy to reduce mortality, morbidity or morbidity among pregnant women or their newborns.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of exercise as an adjunct to medical treatment in children with asthma.
There found no evidence to support the use of inhaled corticosteroids in patients with COPD who do not have a history of COPD and who do have an exacerbation history.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of intensive outpatient rehabilitation for people with acute ischaemic stroke. There is an urgent need for well-designed, adequately powered, double-blinded, placebo-controlled trials with long-term follow-up to assess the effects of intensive rehabilitation on functional outcome.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of omega-3 fatty acids for the prevention or treatment of cardiovascular disease in healthy adults.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of dietary or supplemental omega-3 fatty acids to reduce mortality or morbidity in healthy people.

There is some evidence to support the use of immunosuppressive agents in patients with rheumatoid arthritis. However, there is a need for well-designed RCTs with low risk of bias and well-executed randomised controlled trials with long follow up.
The is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of low-dose antihypertensive drugs to reduce blood pressure in people with pre-existing hypertension.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of educational interventions to prevent or delay the onset of ventilator-associated pneumonia in patients admitted to intensive care units.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of dietary modifications during pregnancy to reduce the risk of preterm birth and morbidity and mortality in women.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of RCTs for the management of patients with LBP and LBP in primary care. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered randomised controlled trials with adequate power to evaluate the effects of interventions on patient outcomes.
There is insufficient evidence to support the use of high-dose chemotherapy regimens in patients with GCTs who have failed first-line chemotherapy.

There is currently insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of ventilatory strategies based on low tidal volume and low end-expiratory pressure in patients with acute respiratory distress syndrome. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials with long-term follow up.

There is insufficient evidence to determine the optimal initial thyroid hormone therapy dose for congenital hypothyroidism. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials with adequate follow-up.

There-to-use therapeutic food (RUTF) appears to be an effective treatment option for children with uncomplicated SAM and MAM who are at risk of severe acute malnutrition. There is some evidence that RUTF may be more effective than ready-to‐use therapeutic foods ( RUTF) in reducing the risk of acute malnutrition, but further studies are needed to confirm this.

There monoclonal antibodies are effective in improving psoriatic arthritis and psoriasis-specific symptoms, but are associated with a higher risk of adverse events than placebo or etanercept. Adalimumab is also associated with an increased risk of stroke.

Thereiotropium is an effective and safe treatment for COPD. It is associated with a significant increase in the risk of COPD exacerbations and death when compared with placebo or monotherapies. However, there is no evidence to support or refute its use in COPD patients with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.

Therepiratory muscle training appears to be effective in improving lung function in people with amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. However, there is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of this intervention in patients with ALS.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of acupuncture or electroacupuncture for the treatment of osteoarthritis of the knee. There is a need for well-conducted randomised controlled trials that compare acupuncture with other treatments for the same knee pain.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of any of the commonly used techniques in the management of chronic LBP. There is a need for well-conducted, well-designed and reported RCTs.
There is insufficient evidence from RCTs to support or refute the use of infliximab biosimilar CT-P13 in patients with inflammatory bowel disease.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of dietary supplements in the treatment of people with anorexia. Further trials are needed to confirm or refute this finding.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of home-based asthma care interventions for children with asthma. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered RCTs that evaluate the effects of such interventions on asthma morbidity and mortality in children and adults with asthma who are at high risk of developing asthma.

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of CPAP for the treatment of sleep apnoea, OSA or OSAH. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered randomised controlled trials with adequate power to detect clinically important differences between therapeutic and non-therapeutic CPAP treatments for OSA and OSA.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the routine use of influenza vaccines in children and adults. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered randomised controlled trials to determine whether influenza vaccines are safe and effective in preventing childhood infections.

There is currently insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to determine whether ART-mediated suppression of HIV-1 replication by ART is beneficial or harmful for kidney function in HIV-infected patients with CKD.

The is insufficient evidence to draw conclusions about the effectiveness of interventions targeting adherence to medication in people with schizophrenia. There is a need for well-designed and reported randomised controlled trials that assess the effectiveness and safety of interventions aimed at improving adherence to antipsychotic medication in patients with schizophrenia and other mental health conditions, as well as to assess the impact of interventions on the quality of care provided by healthcare providers.

There found no evidence to support or refute the use of CPAP in the treatment of OSA. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered randomised controlled trials to determine whether CPAP is beneficial or harmful for patients with OSA and/or their cardiovascular risk factors.
There found no evidence to support or refute the use of inhaled corticosteroids in the treatment of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.

There is currently insufficient evidence to support the use of cognitive behavioural therapy for women with cancer. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered, well-conducted and reported randomised controlled trials evaluating the effects of CBT on cognitive function and quality of life in women with breast cancer.

There found no evidence to support or refute the association between maternal smoking during pregnancy and increased risk of childhood neurodevelopmental disorders. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials with low risk of random errors and high risk of bias.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of psychological interventions for the treatment of neuropathic pain following SCI/D. There is a need for well-designed and reported randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of multiple task walking training in people with Parkinson's disease and cognitive impairment.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of electromyographic biofeedback therapy for people with ischaemic stroke. There is a need for well-conducted, adequately powered, double-blinded, placebo-controlled trials with long-term follow-up and to evaluate the effects of electrostimulation on functional outcome measures.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of aquatic therapy for the treatment of neurological disorders in people with Parkinson's disease.

There is some evidence to support the use of oral acetylcysteine to reduce the number of exacerbations of chronic bronchitis, but the quality of the evidence is low. There is a need for well-designed and reported randomised controlled trials to assess the effect of this drug on mortality, exacerbations and hospital stay in patients with COPD and severe airways obstruction.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of either low or high protein diets to prevent or delay the onset of weight loss in preterm infants.

There found no evidence to support or refute the use of breastfeeding to reduce the risk of asthma, wheeze or allergic disease in children born to mothers with a history of asthma or atopy in the first year of life. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered and reported randomised controlled trials to assess the effects of breastfeeding on asthma and allergic disease outcomes in children.

There found no evidence to support or refute the use of calcium supplementation during pregnancy for preventing pre-eclampsia or preterm birth. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials with adequate power to detect clinically important differences in maternal and neonatal outcomes.

There is some evidence that Internet-based self-help interventions can improve self-efficacy and health status in people with chronic disease. However, there is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of such interventions in the management of chronic diseases.

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the hypothesis that women with PCOS are more likely to develop PCOS than women with untreated PCOS. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials with adequate sample size and adequate allocation concealment in order to establish the relative risk of developing PCOS and its complications.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of acupuncture for treating primary dysmenorrhoea. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered, double-blinded, placebo-controlled trials with adequate power to detect clinically important changes in heart rate variability and sympathetic nerve activity.

There found no evidence to support or refute the use of omega-3 fatty acids in patients undergoing surgery for cancer. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials with adequate power to evaluate the effects of these dietary interventions on mortality, morbidity and quality of life in cancer patients.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of SSRIs in the management of people with motor impairments after stroke.
There is no evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of dietary monounsaturated fatty acids in the treatment of people with atherosclerosis.

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of vitamin D supplementation in women with PCOS or polycystic ovary syndrome. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered, double-blinded, placebo-controlled trials with adequate power to detect clinically important changes in serum 25-hydroxyvitamin D levels.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of exercise rehabilitation as maintenance of physical activity in people with COPD.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of pharmacological interventions to reduce the duration of mechanical ventilation in critically ill patients. There is a need for well designed, conducted, reported and reported randomised controlled trials to determine the effectiveness and safety of such interventions.

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of educational interventions to reduce the number of visits to the emergency department by parents with a child with a fever of ≥ 38.4 ° C. There is a need for well designed, conducted and reported randomised controlled trials to evaluate the effectiveness of interventions to increase the uptake of information about a child's illness in healthcare settings.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of any intervention for the prevention of childhood overweight or obesity in children or adults.

There found no evidence to support or refute the use of breastfeeding education to increase breastfeeding initiation and duration. There is a need for well designed, conducted, reported and reported randomised controlled trials to assess the effect of breastfeeding educational interventions on breastfeeding initiation, duration and breastfeeding initiation in low-income countries.

There is no evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of exercise interventions in the treatment of women with early stage breast cancer. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered and reported RCTs to evaluate the effects of exercise intervention on long-term health outcomes.

There found no evidence to support or refute the use of psychological interventions in women with early breast cancer. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials that compare psychological interventions to other psychological interventions for women with cancer.

There is some evidence to support the use of internet-based psychological interventions for the treatment of psychological distress in cancer patients. However, there is a need for well-designed, adequately powered and reported randomised controlled trials to evaluate the effects of such interventions on quality of life outcomes.

There is some evidence to support the use of immunosuppressive agents in HIV vaccine trials. However, there is a need for further well-conducted RCTs to investigate the efficacy and safety of these vaccines, as well as to evaluate the effectiveness of different vaccines.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of psychosocial interventions for smoking cessation. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered and reported randomised controlled trials to evaluate the effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of such interventions.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of psychological interventions for childhood cancer survivors. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered, well-conducted and reported randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up to determine whether psychological interventions are effective in changing cancer knowledge and behaviour.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of omega 3 fatty acids in the treatment of people with dementia.

Therereatment with mistletoe extracts appears to be effective in improving survival and immunological response in women with head and neck cancer. However, the quality of the evidence is low and the number of trials is small. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered and reported randomised controlled trials with adequate sample sizes and adequate reporting of outcomes.

There review provides some evidence that inhaled corticosteroids are an effective treatment for chronic asthma. However, there is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered and reported RCTs to evaluate the relative effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of inhaled steroids compared to other treatments, such as short-acting beta2-agonists.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of interventions to increase the uptake of influenza vaccines in healthcare settings. There is a need for well designed, conducted and reported randomised controlled trials to assess the effects of interventions on vaccination uptake among healthcare workers and healthcare providers.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of dietary DHA supplementation during pregnancy and lactation for the prevention or treatment of neurodevelopmental disorders in children.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to determine whether vitamin A supplementation in preterm infants with chronic lung disease reduces the risk of death or neurodevelopmental impairment.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of any of the commonly used interventions in the treatment of chronic low-back pain. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered, well-conducted and reported RCTs in this area.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of pharmacological interventions to reduce the risk of OSA in sleep apnoea patients with OSA. There is a need for well-designed, well-conducted and reported randomized controlled trials in this area.

Theals of infliximab are efficacious in induction of remission in patients with active Crohn's disease. However, there is a need for further well-designed RCTs to assess the efficacy of these agents in the management of chronic disease.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of dietary supplements for the treatment of asthma in adults or children.

There is insufficient evidence to determine whether oral cholera vaccines are more effective than placebo in protecting people against Cholera infection. There is a need for well-conducted randomised controlled trials with adequate sample size and adequate duration of follow-up to assess the effect of oral vaccines on mortality, diarrhoea and morbidity.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of survivorship care plans for cancer survivors. There is a need for well-designed RCTs to assess the effect of SCPs on health care utilisation, satisfaction with care and health-related quality of life outcomes.

There is no evidence to support the use of continuous positive airway pressure (CPAP) in patients with acute cardiogenic pulmonary oedema. There is limited evidence to suggest that CPAP is more effective than oxygen therapy or medical treatment alone.

There found no evidence to support or refute the use of inhaled corticosteroids in patients with chronic asthma. There is some evidence to suggest that inhaled steroids may be more effective than metered-dose inhalers in the treatment of chronic asthma, but this conclusion is based on only a small number of studies with small numbers of participants.

Thereercise during pregnancy reduces the risk of developing GDM and may be beneficial for women with normal body mass indexes. However, there is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of exercise during pregnancy for preventing GDM or its complications.

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of telecare to prevent falls in older people with dementia and their carers. There is a need for well-designed, well-conducted and reported randomised controlled trials with low risk of bias, well reported outcome measures and long-term follow-up.

The use of beta blockers in the treatment of women with metastatic ovarian cancer is associated with a modest survival advantage over chemotherapy alone in terms of overall survival, progression-free survival, and overall survival in comparison with chemotherapy alone. However, there is a need for well-designed, adequately powered, and reported randomised controlled trials to determine whether β-blockers are effective in treating metastasis in women with ovarian cancer.

The treatment of women with metastatic breast cancer with either cyclophosphamide, methotrexate or 5-fluorouracil appears to be superior to chemotherapy in terms of overall survival and time to progression. However, there is no evidence to support or refute the use of either of these regimens as first line treatment in patients with advanced breast cancer.
There found no evidence to support or refute the use of iron supplements during pregnancy to reduce mortality or morbidity among women with iron deficiency anemia.
There found no evidence to support or refute the use of nutritional supplements during pregnancy to reduce mortality, morbidity or pre-eclampsia, or morbidity and mortality among pregnant women.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to determine whether acupuncture is an effective treatment for chronic pain in adults with chronic LBP.

There oncogenic human papillomavirus (HPV) types 16 and 18 and cervical intraepithelial neoplasia (CIN2/3) and genital warts were significantly reduced with the use of quadrivalent HPV vaccines compared to placebo. However, there is insufficient evidence to determine whether the vaccine is more effective than the control vaccine or the combination vaccine.

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of antidrug advertising campaigns aimed at reducing alcohol consumption in the workplace. There is a need for well-designed, conducted and reported randomised controlled trials in this field.

There-cutaneous infliximab is effective in induction and maintenance of remission in patients with ulcerative colitis. There is no evidence of a difference in mortality or disability between patients receiving inflixamab and those not in remission.

There is some evidence to support the use of pharmacological interventions to increase the uptake of screening mammography in women aged 50 years or older. However, this evidence is limited by the small number of studies included in this review. There is a need for well-designed and reported randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up and to evaluate the effectiveness of interventions based on the health belief model. Such trials should be of high methodological quality and should report the results of the trials.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of PEEP in patients with acute respiratory distress syndrome. Further RCTs are needed to assess the effect of higher PEEP levels on mortality and morbidity.

There lipid-based nutrient supplements for pregnant and lactating women during pregnancy and postpartum are effective in reducing infant mortality and morbidity in both developed and developing countries. However, there is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of lipid‐based supplements during pregnancy for reducing mortality, morbidity and long-term morbidity among women.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of robotic arm training as a treatment for people with acute stroke.

There found no evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of psychosocial interventions targeting survivors of childhood cancer. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered and reported randomised controlled trials to evaluate the effectiveness and safety of such interventions for survivors and their families.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of the oral pentavalent rotavirus vaccine in preventing diarrhoea or other serious adverse events in children.

There oral cholera vaccines are effective in reducing the risk of death, severe diarrhoea, and symptomatic infection in people aged less than two years of age, and in people at higher risk of infection. There is no evidence to support the use of oral vaccines to prevent cholerea in low- or middle-income countries.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of prone positioning in patients with acute respiratory distress syndrome.
There found no evidence to support or refute the use of dietary iron supplements during pregnancy to reduce mortality, morbidity or morbidity in pregnant women or their newborns.

There is currently insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of psychosocial interventions to reduce the risk of CVD in dementia caregivers. There is a need for well-designed, well-conducted and reported randomised controlled trials with adequate power to detect clinically important differences in CVD risk and mortality.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of CPAP in the treatment of OSAS. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up to determine whether CPAP is an effective treatment for OSAS or whether it is a safe treatment.

There is insufficient evidence from RCTs to support or refute the use of mechanical ventilation as a method of weaning patients from mechanical ventilation. There is a need for well-designed and reported randomised controlled trials to determine whether mechanical ventilation is more effective than airway support ventilation.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of cognitive behavioural interventions for people with dementia and their carers. There is a need for well-designed, well-conducted and reported randomised controlled trials with long-term follow up.

There-adjuvanted H5N1 vaccines are highly immunogenic and show a high degree of cross-reactive immunogenicity when compared to standard vaccines. The combination of adjuvant and pre-p and emic vaccines has been shown to increase the risk of adverse events when compared with standard vaccines, and to reduce the incidence of vaccine-related adverse events. There is a need for well-designed, adequately powered and reported RCTs to assess the efficacy and safety of these vaccines.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of anti-tumor necrosis factor alpha monotherapy in patients with early rheumatoid arthritis.

There is not enough evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of the Choices nutrition logo on the lunchtime menu at work sites. Further research is needed to determine whether the choice of a particular type of food can be influenced by other factors, such as the size of the serving spoon, the type of equipment used, and the types of ingredients used.

There-flow nasal cannula may reduce the risk of nasal trauma compared with nasal CPAP in preterm infants. There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of any one type of rehabilitation intervention after stroke. There is a need for well-designed, well-conducted and reported RCTs with low risk of bias.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of robotic arm training to improve upper limb function in people with and without stroke. There is a need for well-conducted, adequately powered, well-designed and reported RCTs with low risk of bias and high methodological quality.

There is some evidence that self-management interventions, such as self-monitoring of blood pressure, pharmacotherapy and pharmacotherapy, are effective in improving health outcomes in people with chronic kidney disease. However, there is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered and reported randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up to determine the effect sizes of interventions.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of dietary fat in the management of cardiovascular disease in healthy people.

Thereiotropium is an effective short-acting anticholinergic therapy for the treatment of COPD. It is also associated with a significant increase in the risk of asthma exacerbations and death when compared with placebo. However, there is a need for well-designed, adequately powered, double-blinded, placebo-controlled trials with long-term follow-up of at least six months to establish the efficacy of this therapy.

Theremalizumab is effective in reducing allergen-induced exacerbations in adults with mild to moderate asthma. It is also associated with a reduction in the risk of severe asthma exacerbations and a decrease in the use of oral corticosteroids.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of cA2 in the induction of remission in patients with Crohn's disease of the small bowel or colon.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of school-based interventions for preventing or treating aggression in young people. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered randomised controlled trials to evaluate the effectiveness and safety of such interventions.

There found no evidence to support or refute the use of elective right hepatectomy in patients with or without chronic disease. However, there is a need for well-designed, adequately powered randomised controlled trials in this area.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to determine whether electroacupuncture is effective in relieving postoperative pain, nausea and vomiting.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of topical analgesics to reduce pain during immunization procedures in healthy infants.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of dietary advice during pregnancy to reduce the risk of developing eczema and allergic rhinitis in children.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of antibiotics in the treatment of acute exacerbations of COPD. Further well-conducted RCTs are required.

There is no evidence to support the use of cisplatin monotherapy in the treatment of women with advanced or recurrent squamous cell carcinoma of the cervix. There is a need for well-conducted RCTs to evaluate the efficacy and safety of this therapy.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of CPAP in the treatment of OSAHS. There is a need for well-designed randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up to determine whether CPAP is more effective than placebo or no treatment.
There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to support or refute the use of robotic arm training for the rehabilitation of the upper limb after acute stroke.

There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of exercise interventions for fatigue in cancer patients. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered randomised controlled trials with long-term follow-up.

Thereluenza vaccines appear to be effective in reducing the incidence of cardiovascular events and hospitalisations in people aged 60 years or older. However, there is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered, double-blinded, placebo-controlled trials of influenza vaccines in adults, children and adolescents.

There is insufficient evidence from randomised controlled trials to determine whether iron supplementation during pregnancy is beneficial or harmful for women with anaemia and/or iron deficiency anaemia.

There is currently insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of safety-behaviors during exposure therapy for anxiety disorders. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered randomised controlled trials to evaluate the effects of safety behaviour on anxiety disorders, and to investigate whether or not safety behaviour is more effective than other types of treatment.
There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of dietary supplements in the treatment of women with PCOS or polycystic ovary syndrome.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the effectiveness of cognitive-behavioural interventions for people with dementia and their caregivers.
There is insufficient evidence to support or refute the use of intraperitoneal chemotherapy in patients with advanced gastric cancer.

There is not enough evidence to support or refute the use of any specific type of treatment for irritable bowel syndrome. There is a need for well-designed, adequately-powered randomised controlled trials with adequate sample sizes and adequate reporting of outcomes.
